{"id":"2005.13104","submitter":"Naomichi Hatano","authors":"Kanae Mukai and Naomichi Hatano","title":"Discrete-time quantum walk on complex networks for community detection","comments":"18 pages, 10 figures, accepted for publication in Physical Review\n  Research","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 2, 023378 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.2.023378","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.data-an","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We define the discrete-time quantum walk on complex networks and utilize it\nfor community detection. We numerically show that the quantum walk with the\nFourier coin is localized in a community to which the initial node belongs.\nMeanwhile, the quantum walk with the Grover coin tends to be localized around\nthe initial node, not over a community. The probability of the classical random\nwalk on the same network converges to the uniform distribution with a\nrelaxation time generally a priori. We thus claim that the time average of the\nprobability of the Fourier-coin quantum walk on complex networks reveals the\ncommunity structure more explicitly than that of the Grover-coin quantum walk\nand a snapshot of the classical random walk. We first demonstrate our method of\ncommunity detection for a prototypical three-community network, producing the\ncorrect grouping. We then apply our method to two real-world networks, namely\nZachary's karate club and the US Airport network. We successfully reveals the\ncommunity structure, the two communities of the instructor and the\nadministrator in the former and major airline companies in the latter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 27 May 2020 00:43:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-01"}
